				<p><p>I will try not to skip too many steps. Assuming a Global coordinate frame at the base and the arm is fully extended along the <strong>Y</strong>-axis of the base frame. 
<a href="https://i.stack.imgur.com/HE9ds.jpg" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/HE9ds.jpg" alt="enter image description here"></a></p>

<p>Since SCARA has four joints, we will create four 6D spatial vectors (screws) ${ }_{i}$ with respect to a global coordinate frame. Keep in mind that <strong>all spatial vectors are described with respect to the global frame</strong>. Also ${ }_{i}$ will describe the axis around which rotation takes place and along which translation takes place. Basically, we assume a screw motion for every joint along its <strong>Z</strong>-axis.</p>

<p>The first three elements of vector ${ }_{1}$ (for joint 1) will the linear velocity on the screw axis, let's call it ${v}_{i}$. The last three elements are the rotation of the joint with respect to the global coordinate frame, regardless if there are other joints preceding it. Let's call it ${ }_{i}$ and it will always be a unit vector.$${ }_{ }=\left[{\begin{matrix}{v}_{i}\\{ }_{i} \end{matrix}}\right]$$</p>

<p>For the first joint the axis of rotation coincides with the global <strong>Z</strong>-axis. Therefore ${ }_{1}$ is $${ }_{1}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$</p>

<p>If you are not sure how I came up with it consider the following. if the z axis of the joint was along the y axis of the global frame then the ${ }_{1}$ would be $${ }_{y}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\1\\0 \end{matrix}}\right]$$. if it was along the x-axis then it would be $${ }_{x}=\left[{\begin{matrix}1\\0\\0 \end{matrix}}\right]$$. And of course it was along the z axis but pointing downwards then: $${ }_{-z}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\-1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$.</p>

<p>Now let's focus on ${v}_{1}$. We need a point ${q}_{1}$ that will give us the distance of the joint from the origin. The distance is L1 along the z-axis, therefore: $${q}_{1}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\L1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$ </p>

<p>We rotate ${q}_{1}$ with the unit angular velocity ${ }_{1}$ (cross product) and we have $${v}_{1}=\left[-{ }_{1} \times {q}_{1} \right] =- \left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\1 \end{matrix}}\right] \times \left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\L1 \end{matrix}}\right] = \left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\0 \end{matrix}}\right] $$</p>

<p>Therefore $${ }_{1}=\left[{\begin{matrix}{v}_{1}\\{ }_{1} \end{matrix}}\right]=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\0\\0\\0\\1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$.</p>

<p>Simillarly we have $${ }_{2}=\left[{\begin{matrix}{v}_{2}\\{ }_{2} \end{matrix}}\right]=\left[{\begin{matrix}L2\\0\\0\\0\\0\\1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$</p>

<p>For the third joint the ${ }_{3}$ is <strong>0</strong> because it is prismatic and ${v}_{3}$ is the unit vector $${v}_{3}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\1 \end{matrix}}\right]$$ making ${ }_{3}$ $${ }_{3}=\left[{\begin{matrix}{v}_{3}\\0 \end{matrix}}\right]=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\0\\1\\0\\0\\0 \end{matrix}}\right]$$. </p>

<p>For joint 4 $${v}_{4}=-\left[{\begin{matrix} 0\\0\\1\end{matrix}}\right] \times \left[{\begin{matrix}0\\L2+L3\\L1-d1\end{matrix}}\right] = \left[{\begin{matrix}0\\L2+L3\\0\end{matrix}}\right]$$</p>

<p>$${ }_{4}=\left[{\begin{matrix}0\\L2+L3\\0\\0\\0\\1\end{matrix}}\right]$$</p>

<p>Now the spatial vectors ${ }_{i}$ describe the axes of rotation of all the joints. Keep in mind that some authors have $v$ and $ $ switch places. For example the paper you are mentioning. This is fine as long as you are consistent throughout. </p>

<p>This example is being worked out in "A mathematical introduction to robotic manipulation" I have linked in my previous answer on page 88. </p>

<p>These are the basics of the screw theory description. Similarly we can create a wrench 6D vector <strong> </strong> with the linear and the angular (torques) forces. As you can tell by now, screw theory is a method to describe the manipulator (like the DH parameters) and not a mobility formula like the Chebychev-Kutzbach-Grubler method. The paper you are referencing stacks the spatial vectors (it calls them twists) ${ }_{i}$ and the wrenches ${ }{i}$ to create a twist matrix and then analyze their constraint using the union and the reciprocal of the twists. Those are vector functions that the screw theory can take advantage of.  </p>

<p>I am not sure if my answer helps you but the paper you are mentioning requires a relatively strong understanding of screw theory and vector algebra to make sense.</p>

<p>Please let me know if you need more clarifications.</p>

